# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __neg__, __pos__, __abs__ across all 8 mp subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 8 classes x 3 methods = 24 rows.
# __neg__: false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# __pos__: false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# __abs__: false for all 8 — not in any type's own __dict__.
# All 24 values are false.
# The proxy types (_BaseSetProxy, _BaseDictProxy, BaseListProxy) are the most
#   analytically interesting subjects here. _BaseSetProxy proxies set, which
#   has no __neg__, __pos__, or __abs__ — set is a collection, not a number.
#   _BaseDictProxy proxies dict — dict has no unary numeric operators.
#   BaseListProxy proxies list — list has no unary numeric operators.
#   Consequently, even the proxy types, which in some earlier waves (wave 658)
#   exposed __add__ and __mul__ via BaseListProxy, do not define any unary
#   numeric operators in their own __dict__.
# Wave 658 established that BaseListProxy.__add__ and BaseListProxy.__mul__
#   are true — the only true results in mp waves 658–669. All three unary
#   numeric operators tested here (wave 670) are absent even from BaseListProxy,
#   because list defines no __neg__, __pos__, or __abs__ (list items have
#   magnitude but the list container itself does not).
# multiprocessing is a process-based concurrency library; its types interact
#   exclusively through explicit method calls, subprocess lifecycle management,
#   and IPC — never through Python's unary numeric data model operators.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

